com.camerontec.catalys.util.marketdata

Interface IDetailUpdate

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    FixMarketDataInstrument, StandardInstrument

    public interface IDetailUpdate
    Classes maintaining an internal detail can allow the detail to be updated externally using these methods.

    Detail is defined as the unaggregated market data - ie there can be multiple entries for a given price level.

    Individual detail entries can be uniquely identified in the following ways:

    • Position within the list of entries - most competitive first, starting at zero.
    • Unique internally generated int identifier associated with each entry.

    Identifying detail entries using externally supplied identifiers

    Often there will be some external identifier which the market data source (eg an exchange) uses to track detail entries. It is up to the service writer to map this external identifier to the internal int id's used by this interface (as in StandardInstrument). When a new detail entry is created, add the new detail entry by calling the addDetailEntry method. Then look at the returned DetailEntry object to get the internally generated int id used by StandardInstrument to uniquely identify that entry. If necessary store a mapping between that internal id and the id used externally (which may be a String, for example). Then when a change or delete for a detail entry comes in, use the map to look up the internal detail id from the externally supplied id. Then use the internal id in the appropriate StandardInstrument change or delete detail method.

    • Method Detail

      • addDetailEntry

        IDetailEntry addDetailEntry(boolean buy,
                            int position,
                            int price,
                            int qty,
                            IMarketDataItem[] values)
        Adds a new detail entry with the given characteristics to the list of existing detail entries at the specified price level.

        Processing of the values array terminates once an entry with a 0 fieldID is encountered. This allows an array to be reused for passing in events.

        If one of the explicit fields, (ie buy, position, price or qty), also is specified in the values array, the values array entry is ignored - in other words the explicit field value takes precedence.

        Note that StandardUpdateEntry is an IMarketData, so that an array of StandardUpdateEntry's can be passed in as the values if you wish.

        Parameters:
        buy - True if this is a buy side entry.
        position - Optional position of this entry within full detail (starting at 0). May be -1 in which case it will be added to the end of the list of existing detail entries at this price level.
        price - Price level of this entry.
        qty - Quantity of entry.
        values - Any additional information associated with this entry - for example the broker associated with the entry. May be null.
        Returns:
        The object used to store this entry's details.

      • changeDetail

        void changeDetail(IDetailEntry[] buyDetail,
                  IDetailEntry[] sellDetail,
                  gnu.trove.map.hash.TLongObjectHashMap<IDetailEntry> idMap)
        Replaces whole detail in a single call.

        Any previous detail information is discarded.

        The most competitive entry should be at index 0 in the array.

        Processing of the array will stop at the first entry with qty == 0. This means that the same fixed size array object can be reused for passing in data in successive calls, since only non empty entries in the array will be processed - extra entries will be ignored.

        Parameters:
        buyDetail - Buy side detail entries
        sellDetail - Sell side detail entries
        idMap - Used for mapping external ID's on the detail entries to the ID's used to reference the detail entries internally. May be null, in which case any ID's on the detail entries are ignored completely.

      • changeDetailEntryByID

        IDetailEntry changeDetailEntryByID(int entryID,
                                   int position,
                                   int price,
                                   int qty,
                                   StandardUpdateEntry[] changes)
        The detail entry with the given ID is changed to contain the specified values.

        Note that the position of the entry may be changed.

        If no such entry exists, one is created.

        Processing of the changes array terminates once an entry with a 0 fieldID is encountered. This allows an array to be reused for passing in events.

        If one of the explicit fields, (ie position, price or qty), also is specified in the changes array, the changes array entry is ignored - in other words the explicit field value takes precedence.

        Parameters:
        entryID - The ID of the entry to be changed.
        position - The position (starting at 0) of the entry. Negative means no change.
        price - Price level of this entry.
        qty - Quantity of entry.
        changes - Any additional information associated with this entry - for example the broker associated with the entry. May be null.
        Returns:
        The object used to store the changed entry.

      • changeDetailEntryByPosition

        IDetailEntry changeDetailEntryByPosition(boolean buy,
                                         int position,
                                         int price,
                                         int qty,
                                         StandardUpdateEntry[] changes)
        The detail entry at this position and side (buy or sell) is changed to contain the specified values.

        If no such entry exists, one is created.

        Processing of the changes array terminates once an entry with a 0 fieldID is encountered. This allows an array to be reused for passing in events.

        If one of the explicit fields, (ie buy, position, price or qty), also is specified in the changes array, the changes array entry is ignored - in other words the explicit field value takes precedence.

        Parameters:
        buy - True if this is a buy side entry.
        position - The position (starting at 0) of the entry. Negative means no change.
        price - Price level of this entry.
        qty - Quantity of entry.
        changes - Any additional information associated with this entry - for example the broker associated with the entry. May be null.
        Returns:
        The object used to store the changed entry.
